We will use OpenSSL to create a private key and a self-signed certificate valid for 365 days, specifically generated for your local domain name my-app.com.

Run this command on your controlplane terminal:

Bash
openssl req -x509 -nodes -days 365 -newkey rsa:2048 \
  -keyout ~/kube/networking/Ingress/my-app.key \
    -out ~/kube/networking/Ingress/my-app.crt \
      -subj "/CN=my-app.com/O=LocalLab"
      This creates two files in your folder: my-app.key (your private key) and my-app.crt (your public certificate).

      Step 2: Store the Certificate in a Kubernetes Secret
      An Ingress resource cannot read raw certificate files directly from the Linux hard drive. It requires them to be securely stored inside the cluster as a TLS Secret.

      Run this command to import your fresh keys into your active namespace:

      Bash
      kubectl create secret tls my-app-tls-secret \
        --cert=/home/system/kube/networking/tls/my-app.crt \
          --key=/home/system/kube/networking/tls/my-app.key
          Step 3: Update the Ingress Resource with the TLS Block

[19:29:17] system@controlplane:~/kube/networking/tls$ curl -k -H "Host: my-app.com" https://192.168.31.157:32266/app1
Hello , Welcome to App1
[19:30:07] system@controlplane:~/kube/networking/tls$ curl -k -H "Host: my-app.com" https://192.168.31.157:32266/app2
Hello, Welcome to App2
